original_title: Manhattan: La Salle Place - Amsterdam Avenue
text:
La Salle Place (W. 125th Street), north side, east from Amsterdam Avenue to Roosevelt Square. The converging thoroughfare at the right is the present W. 125th (formerly Manhattan) Street. Adjoining the Daniel Reeves structure is the 2 story McGuire Building and same forms the apex of this triangular block.

April 1928.

George L. Balgue,

W. 124th Street, east from Amsterdam Avenue and across same. View No. 2 shows mainly the south side and upon which stands 15 five story tenement houses owned by John D. Rockefeller Jr. These, consisting of Nos. 432 to 400 W. 124th Street, are to be demolished according to the New York Times of October 5, 1938. No plans for the future use of this site have yet been announced. Backing up to this row is the rear of the Lincoln School of Teachers College on 123rd Street.

August 1930
View 2: August 24, 1938.

George L. Balgue
P.L. Sperr

West 124th Street, east from Amsterdam Avenue. At the left, at Morningside Avenue, is a clearance upon which stood until recently, the buildings owned by John D. Rockefeller. To their rears abutted the rear of the Lincoln School of Teachers College. This is now opened to view. The institutional structure in the center background is Sydenham Hospital.

Spring, 1940

P. L. Sperr
